Le Havre, France

A great location from which to defend against the English.

La Havre and the town on the opposite side of the river, Honfleur, sit at the mouth of the Seine and were major ports during the Hundred Years War and the Viking invasions. Normandy is a major artistic center since the Impressionist movement and the local galleries have works from many famous painters. I missed the local cliffs at Êtretat but I’m assured they’re worth visiting.

Length of Stay 1 day
Transportation Three hour drive from Mont-Saint-Michel
Major Sights Saint-Joseph’s Church, Museum of Modern Art André Malraux, Êtretat
Restaurant Recommendations N/A

Saint Joseph’s church was rebuilt following WWII using a reinforced concrete design by Auguste Perret, a mentor to Le Corbusier. The Modern Art Museum Andre Malraux is great and features many French masters.

The sister town of Honfleur, on the other side of the mouth of the Seine, was fortified by French King Charles V during the Hundred Years War.

The town’s church, Saint-Catherine, is the largest wood church in France.
